%20out%3C%2Fa%3E%E2%80%9D%2C%20demonstrating%20%E2%80%9Cheart%E2%80%9D%2C%20%E2%80%9Cgrit%E2%80%9D%20and%20%E2%80%9Cdetermination%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EBut%20do%20horses%20even%20know%20they%20are%20in%20a%20race%2C%20let%20alone%20have%20a%20desire%20to%20win%20it%3F%20Do%20they%20understand%20what%20it%20means%20when%20their%20nose%20is%20the%20first%20one%20to%20pass%20the%20post%3F%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EBased%20on%20decades%20of%20experience%20and%20everything%20we%20know%20about%20horse%20behaviour%2C%20I%20think%20the%20most%20plausible%20answer%20is%20%E2%80%9Cno%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Ch2%3EFrom%20the%20horse's%20perspective%3C%2Fh2%3E%20%3Cp%3EFrom%20a%20horse's%20perspective%2C%20there%20are%20few%20intrinsic%20rewards%20for%20winning%20a%20race.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EReaching%20the%20end%20might%20mean%20relief%20from%20the%20pressure%20to%20keep%20galloping%20at%20high%20speed%20and%20hits%20from%20the%20jockey's%20whip%2C%20but%20the%20same%20is%20true%20for%20all%20the%20horses%20once%20they%20pass%20the%20finishing%20post.%20If%20the%20race%20is%20close%2C%20the%20horse%20that%20eventually%20wins%20might%20even%20be%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fjournals.plos.org%2Fplosone%2Farticle%3Fid%3D10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0015622%5C%22%3Ewhipped%20more%20often%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20the%20final%20stages%20than%20horses%20further%20back%20in%20the%20field.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ESo%20while%20being%20first%20to%20reach%20the%20winning%20post%20can%20be%20crucially%20important%20to%20the%20horse's%20human%20connections%2C%20there%20is%20very%20little%20direct%2C%20intrinsic%20benefit%20to%20the%20horse%20that%20would%20motivate%20it%20to%20voluntarily%20gallop%20faster%20to%20achieve%20this%20outcome.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ESo%20does%20a%20horse%20even%20know%20it's%20in%20a%20race%3F%20Again%2C%20the%20answer%20is%20likely%20%E2%80%9Cno%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ERunning%20(cantering%20or%20galloping)%20is%20a%20quintessential%20horse%20behaviour%20and%20horses%20voluntarily%20run%20together%20in%20groups%20when%20given%20the%20opportunity%20%E2%80%93%20even%20in%20races%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.thenationalnews.com%2Fworld%2F2022%2F08%2F22%2Friderless-race-horses-take-to-the-streets-in-central-italy-in-pictures%2F%5C%22%3Ewithout%20jockeys%3C%2Fa%3E.%20However%2C%20there%20are%20a%20number%20of%20reasons%20to%20think%20horses%20have%20not%20evolved%20a%20desire%20to%20%E2%80%9Cwin%E2%80%9D%20during%20a%20group%20gallop.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EHorses%20are%20social%20animals.%20In%20the%20wild%2C%20to%20minimise%20their%20individual%20exposure%20to%20predators%2C%20they%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fjournals.plos.org%2Fplosone%2Farticle%3Fid%3D10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0258944%5C%22%3Esynchronise%20their%20movement%3C%2Fa%3E%20with%20other%20horses%20in%20their%20group.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThis%20synchronisation%20includes%20maintaining%20similar%20speeds%20to%20other%20group%20members%20(to%20keep%20the%20group%20together)%2C%20being%20alert%20to%20the%20positions%20of%20their%20own%20body%20and%20their%20neighbours'%20to%20avoid%20collisions%2C%20and%20adapting%20their%20speed%20to%20the%20terrain%20and%20environmental%20cues%20that%20indicate%20upcoming%20danger%20or%20obstacles.%20In%20the%20wild%2C%20%E2%80%9Cwinning%E2%80%9D%20%E2%80%93%20that%20is%2C%20arriving%20first%2C%20long%20before%20other%20group%20members%20%E2%80%93%20could%20even%20be%20a%20negative%2C%20exposing%20the%20%E2%80%9Cwinner%E2%80%9D%20to%20an%20increased%20risk%20of%20predation.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThis%20collective%20behaviour%20is%20the%20opposite%20of%20what%20owners%2C%20trainers%20and%20punters%20want%20from%20horses%20during%20a%20race.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Ch2%3EThe%20horse's%20preferences%20(and%20how%20riders%20override%20them)%3C%2Fh2%3E%20%3Cp%3EHorse%20races%20depend%20on%20two%20horse-related%20factors%3A%20the%20horse's%20innate%20tendency%20to%20synchronise%20with%20other%20horses%2C%20and%20its%20ability%20to%20be%20trained%20to%20ignore%20these%20tendencies%20in%20response%20to%20cues%20from%20the%20jockey%20during%20a%20race.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ETrainers%20and%20jockeys%20also%20harness%20the%20preferences%20of%20individual%20horses.%20Some%20horses%20are%20averse%20to%20bunching%20up%20with%20others%20during%20the%20race%2C%20so%20jockeys%20let%20them%20move%20to%20the%20front%20of%20the%20field%20(these%20are%20%E2%80%9C%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.racingnsw.com.au%2Fnews%2Ffeature-articles%2Fthe-art-of-the-front-runner-timing-a-jockeys-best-friend%2F%5C%22%3Efront%20runners%3C%2Fa%3E%E2%80%9D).%20Other%20horses%20seek%20the%20security%20of%20the%20group%2C%20so%20jockeys%20let%20them%20remain%20in%20the%20bunch%20until%20closer%20to%20the%20winning%20post%20(these%20are%20%E2%80%9Ccome-from-behind%E2%80%9D%20winners).%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EJockeys%20use%20several%20different%20interventions%20to%20override%20the%20horse's%20innate%20tendency%20to%20synchronise.%20These%20might%20include%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cul%3E%20%3Cli%3E%20%3Cp%3Edirecting%20the%20horses%20to%20travel%20much%20closer%20to%20the%20other%20horses%20(risking%20the%20sometimes%20fatal%20injuries%20we%20sometimes%20see%20at%20the%20track)%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3C%2Fli%3E%20%3Cli%3E%20%3Cp%3Etravelling%20at%20speeds%20not%20of%20the%20horse's%20choosing%20(usually%20at%20far%20higher%20speeds%20and%20for%20longer%20durations%2C%20and%20often%20maintained%20by%20use%20of%20the%20whip)%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3C%2Fli%3E%20%3Cli%3E%20%3Cp%3Epreventing%20the%20horse%20from%20changing%20course%20to%20adapt%20its%20position%20relative%20to%20other%20horses%20in%20the%20field%20(directing%20its%20path%20via%20pressure%20on%20the%20mouth%20from%20the%20bit%20or%20taps%20from%20the%20whip).%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3C%2Fli%3E%20%3C%2Ful%3E%20%3Cp%3EDuring%20the%20early%20stages%20of%20a%20race%2C%20jockeys%20rely%20on%20horses'%20innate%20desire%20to%20remain%20with%20the%20group%20to%20ensure%20they%20maintain%20the%20physical%20effort%20required%20to%20keep%20in%20touch%20with%20the%20front%20runners.%20This%20tendency%20may%20then%20be%20overruled%20so%20the%20horse%20will%20act%20independently%20of%20the%20group%2C%20leave%20it%20behind%20and%20come%20to%20the%20front%20to%20hopefully%20win.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Ch2%3ENo%20concept%20of%20being%20in%20a%20race%3C%2Fh2%3E%20%3Cp%3ESo%20horses%20most%20likely%20have%20no%20concept%20of%20being%20in%20a%20%E2%80%9Crace%E2%80%9D%2C%20where%20the%20goal%20of%20their%20galloping%20is%20to%20get%20to%20a%20certain%20location%20on%20the%20track%20before%20any%20of%20the%20other%20horses.%20However%2C%20they%20undoubtedly%20know%20what%20it's%20like%20to%20%3Cem%3Ebe%3C%2Fem%3E%20in%20a%20race.%20That%20is%2C%20they%20learn%20through%20prior%20experience%20and%20training%20what%20is%20likely%20to%20happen%20and%20what%20to%20do%20during%20a%20race.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EAnd%20with%20jockeys%20and%20trainers%20who%20understand%20the%20individual%20preferences%20of%20their%20horses%20to%20maximise%20their%20chances%20during%20the%20race%2C%20there%20will%20always%20be%20one%20horse%20that%20reaches%20that%20part%20of%20the%20track%20designated%20the%20winning%20post%20before%20the%20other%20horses%20in%20the%20group.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EBut%20as%20for%20winning%20horses%20understanding%20they%20are%20there%20to%20%E2%80%9Cwin%E2%80%9D%3F%20It's%20far%20more%20likely%20it%20is%20the%20combination%20of%20natural%20ability%2C%20physical%20fitness%20and%20jockey%20skill%20that%20accounts%20for%20which%20horse%20wins%2C%20rather%20than%20any%20innate%20desire%20by%20that%20horse%20to%20get%20to%20the%20winning%20post%20before%20the%20other%20horses.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fprofiles%2Fcathrynne-henshall-572585%5C%22%3ECathrynne%20Henshall%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20Lecturer%2C%20School%20of%20Agricultural%2C%20Environmental%20and%20Veterinary%20Sciences%2C%20%3Cem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Finstitutions%2Fcharles-st